		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<div></div><br><blockquote><hr>josahd wrote:<br><div></div><p>Frod,<br><br>Decrepit skin is the main reason I'm in favor of adding some type of downward scaling ability, probably via some type of defensive proc, to warriors.<br><br>However, this isn't something that can be, nor should be addressed via the typical methods- ie, modifying relative melee mitigation values for warriors. Because it's a downward scaling ability, and mitigation is upward scaling, in order to narrow the gap much at all at the low end, the difference would be obscene as melee damage scales upward.</p><p></p><hr><p></p><p>I agree with this fairly strongly. The last thing that's needed at this time is another segregation of scaling and non scaling tools, because it only increases the distance at both ends. At this point, there's a fairly strong X pattern if you look at Knight/Warrior tanking scales, when the X axis is DI, and the Y axis is Damage Taken, especially when the PoR spells are considered (although it existed at a lower scale prior to that point). Decrepit skin is powerful, but it appears on paper that Ward of Tunare is even moreso.</p><p></p><p></p><hr><br><br>Also bear in mind that mock alone is a downward scaling ability that absorbs better than half of the theoretical max absorption of decrepit skin. Furthermore, the mana cost of decrepit skin will prevent full-time use, especially if you're in a fast-pulling exp group (I can't maintain all of my utility full time now in a fast pulling exp group, adding in another 15 mana/tick isn't feasible without impacting other abilities, thus, it won't be up full time).<br><div></div><p>Message Edited by josahd on <span class="date_text">03-09-2006</span><span class="time_text">04:21 PM</span><br></p><hr></blockquote><blockquote dir="ltr"><p><br>I'm trying to understand the meaning of the first part of the statement. Mock's max absorption is 500hp. If I understand correctly, you're saying that it absorbs a max of 1k per minute if cast twice per minute, or 4k for the 4-ish mins max duration of Decrepit Skin.</p><p>Now, the issue with this of course is that you then discuss the mana cost of Decrepit skin, which at 450 for the 4.2 min duration (or 25 ticks) comes out to 18 mana per tick.</p><p>In that same time with Cyclone Blade being used 9 times to get a little less than half of the limit of that one cast of Decrepit skin, we've spent 3150 END... a dramatic cost difference, especially considering the current state of END regeneration (if we're using mock, we're fighting, thus we're regenning at a max of 26/tick, with of course no spell regen, and no mana pres focus, and no item regen... it would take an estimated downtime of 121 ticks, or 20 minutes to regenerate for what is in essence slightly less than *half* the downward scaling protection that Decrepit skin, for 450 mana, which won't cost 450 mana with any mana pres focus. I'm not real sure if buff extension foci will work on it, but if it does, it stretches the cost/benefit ratio even further.</p><p>That's a fairly huge differential if you ask me.</p><p>Now, it's true that I do not draw on my endurance pool for as large of a portion of my power source, it essentially robs me of cyclone blade usage, and ANY discipline usage without a rather dramatic amount of downtime.</p><p>Now, I'm glad you agree with the essential issue, particularly when it comes to comparing ward/skin with what warriors received with mock, but something absolutely has to break, as it's pushed the &quot;downward scaling advantage&quot; &quot;X&quot; intersection essentially ABOVE the level of group mobs, which in turn makes knights superior in what is supposed to be the primary strength of warriors, which is the rate at which heals must be cast upon the tank.</p><p>If warriors do not have a longer heal interval than knights, then warriors have no use in Everquest, at all. It means that there is absolutely nothing that a warrior excels in beyond raid tanking. Every offensive &quot;strength&quot; that we have is outdone by the real DPS classes, and if our defensive prowess falls behind... as it recently has.. then the game is actually completely over for warriors in the group game of everquest.</p><p>This is the most serious issue that's ever faced warriors in EQ, moreso than taunt in Planes of Power, and I do not intend to let it be overlooked under any circumstance.</p><p></p></blockquote>
								<p><div style="width: 100%; height: 120; overflow: hidden;">
								
