			>
			<div></div><div></div><div></div>Because they aren't spamming 4 spells in an endless cycle. Versus the kinds of mobs Knights are supposed to have more parity in tanking, they live for less than 30 seconds.<br><br>When pressed about Paladin assertions that their alledged carpal tunnel syndrome succeptability would have been ended by adding 1/3rd more aggro to their stuns, but also adding 1/3rd to the refresh they objected. They WANT to be ale to spam over and above what is necessary and proper to obtain and hold aggro.<br><br>Sure a Wizard, Monk, or Rogue can steal aggro. But aggro management is the responsibility of all players. Each of these classes have measures they can use to reduce their aggro. Wizards are well advised in groups to do so particularly since it preserves their abiilty to sustain high DPS output. And Wizards are well advised to let it loose for the killshot - a point where there wil be no repercusions for overnuking.<br><br>SoE is not responsible to give classes that tank group mobs tools that make up for others not knowing how to play their classes.<br><br>It's true that Wariors are able to build up aggro and that towards the end of a long fight high DPS classes can go all out. But, that's Warriors vs. not group mobs - mobs where Warirors are supposed to have a decided advantage.<br><br>While SK's can complain they don't have as much aggro as they would like, in 10 back to back 30 second fights, group and raid clearing yard trash typ mobs where they are supposed to have some parity, SK aggro is very much like Warirors aggro only more flexible. Paladins have jack nothing to complain about. They put us all to shame, particularly vs. stunable group mobs where they not only get aggro they get control of the fight through stuns that Warirors and SK's can't even dream of having.<br><br>Find any Knight that has made the same effort as most raid Warirors make to obtain and hold aggro -<br><br>Using their highest swing aggro weapon setup, putting aggro augs on it, acquiring a Symbol of the Planesmaster/Gloves of the Crimson Sigil, acquiring an EoA item and maintaining one ever since PoTime - heck even ASKING for EoA to appear on their Epic or an EoA item to be aded to the game. Such Knights are the exception, not the rule as with Warirors.<br><br>SoE adjusted Knight aggro and Knight weapon ratios to allow their use of sword and board. There's no denying it or explaining it away.<br><br>Make sword and board practical for Warirors and in lesser content we can equip a shield and focus our efforts on things other than aggro and defence just like knights. Our heavy DPS would make up for a lack of <u>group friendly utility</u> - which is the only downward scaling advantage Knights have that means anything when we are all easily tanking the content.<br><br>Yes, sword and board makes Warirors better tanks vs. harder content too. But <u>we are supposed to be better tanks</u>. Sword and board should never have been a Knight advantage. <div></div><p>Message Edited by Battleblade-Xegony on <span class=date_text>03-10-2006</span> <span class=time_text>04:59 AM</span>	
